 Valuable things, activities and income generation in (away from cities) Mexico: 
 factoring in social and public capital* 
 Paul Winters a,*, Benjamin Davis b, Leonardo Place c 
 Graduate School of Farming-based &amp; useful thing/valuable supply Money flow, School of Money flow, 
 University of New England, Armidale, NSW 2351, Australia 
 ESAE/Room C-309, Food and Farming-based Organisation, Small glass containere delle Terme de Caracalla, 00100 Rome, Italy 
 c Inter-American Development Bank, 1300 New York Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20577, USA 
 a 
 
 b 
 
 Received 19 June 2001 ; accepted 14 November 2001 
 
 Abstract 
 Over the last few years, there has been increasing focus in the (away from cities) development books on the multiple income-creating 
 activities begun/tried by (away from cities) families and the importance of valuable things in deciding/figuring out the ability to begin/try these activities. 
 Controlling for the endogeneity of activity choice and applying Lee's (big statement based on very little information) of Amemiya's two-step estimator to a 
 (happening together) equation model, household returns to valuable things from many activities are explored for the Mexico ejido part/area. To 
 includes the many (numbers that change/things that change) representing social and public capital into the analysis, factor analysis is used. The results 
 point to/show that the valuable thing position of the household has a significant effect on household participation in income-creating 
 activities and returns to those activities. What's more, including measures of social and public capital into the analysis 
 show that these valuable things play an important role in income-creating activities and that the influence is dependent on the type 
 of social and public capital as well as the particular activity. 
