 Keywords: Jobs; Mexico; Respect; Public capital; Farming-based families; Changed moving backward 
 
 1. Introduction 
 Over the last few years, there has been increasing focus 
 within the (away from cities) development books on what is 
 referred to as (away from cities) jobs and job (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing). A key feature of the idea  of jobs 
 is the link between valuable things, activities and income and 
 
 * 
 
 Paper prepared for the Food and Farming Organization 
 (related to a large area) Office for Latin America and the Caribbean for the 
 project: Social Capital and (away from cities) Job Plans in Latin 
 America: Effects/results/suggestions for Project Putting into use. 
 * Corresponding author. 
 E-mail address: pwinters@metz.une.edu.au (P. Winters). 
 
 the role of the institutional big picture  in deciding/figuring out the 
 use of and returns to valuable things. For example, Ellis (2000) 
 defines a job as making up "the valuable things (natural, physical, human, (money-related) and respect), the 
 activities and the access to these (judged by institutions and social relations) that together decide/figure out the 
 living gained by an individual or household". Job (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) is then the process by which 
 families construct a (many different kinds of people or things) (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection) of activities 
 and valuable things to survive and improve their standard of 
 living (Ellis, 2000). 
 The jobs approach has played an important 
 role in highlighting the many activities begun/tried 
 
