 by (away from cities) families, the importance of valuable things in deciding/figuring out the ability to begin/try activities, the energetic nature of the actions of (away from cities) families and the 
 link between the (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) of valuable things and activities 
 (Barrett and Reardon, 2000). (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from developing countries points to/shows that (away from cities) families depend on 
 some valuable things and employ many activities to 
 create income. Especially, there has been strong 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) pointing to/showing the increasing importance of (away from cities) 
 non-farm activities. Reardon et al. (2001), for example, show that, based on a set of studies from Latin 
 America, (away from cities) non-farm activities make up 40% of 
 (away from cities) household income. What's more, the (popular thing/general way things are going) is toward greater non-farm activities for (away from cities) residents. 
 While the jobs approach has added/has given to 
 our understanding of (away from cities) household behaviour, there 
 has been little scientific examination of the approach. 
 Some recent studies have recognised the role 
 of a (many different kinds of people or things) set of valuable things in income-creating activities. For example, Lanjouw (1999, 2001) examines 
 non-farm income in Ecuador and El Salvador using 
 valuable things such as workers (education, reading and writing ability), natural capital (land) and public capital (electrification, 
 water connection) as explanatory (numbers that change/things that change). Winters 
 et al. (2001) explore the role of valuable things, including social 
 and public capital, in the decision to move. Place 
 and Reardon (2001), and De Janvry and Sadoulet 
 (2001) explore the importance of natural, human, 
 social and public capital in the generation of income 
 in Nicaragua and Mexico, (match up each pair of items in order). While recognising the importance of valuable things in income-creating 
 activities, these studies do not think about/believe both the (happening together) nature of (strategy for investing money wisely) and the selectivity 
 bias created by the decision to participate in an activity. 
 One recent study that does think about/believe these issues is 
 by Taylor and Yunez-Naude (2000). Their paper focuses on the returns to schooling from a (many different kinds of people or things) set of 
 activities in (away from cities) Mexico widening (serious thought/something to think about/respect) to 
 both household head and family education. Taylor and 
 Yunez-Naude's paper is interesting from an econometric point of view in that they carefully face/deal with issues 
 affecting bias and inefficiency in limit/guideline guesses. 
 By controlling for endogeneity of activity choice and 
 using Lee's (big statement based on very little information) of Amemiya's two-step estimator in a (happening together)-equation model, the resulting estimators are asymptotically (producing more with less waste) than 
 other two-stage estimators, such as the commonly used 
 Heckman procedure. 
 
 In this study, we use the same econometric approach as Taylor and Yunez-Naude to explore job plans in the Mexican ejido part/area. Unlike 
 Taylor and Yunez-Naude, our main interest lies in 
 exploring the importance of community level factors, 
 especially social and public capital (numbers that change/things that change), in the 
 participation in and returns to income-creating activities. Evidence hints that along with 
 other forms of capital, social and public capital play 
 an important role in household income-generation. 
 For example, an analysis of Tanzanian families 
 shows that higher levels of respect are related to greater levels of expense (Narayan and 
 Pritchett, 1999). Understanding the role of social and 
 public capital in income generation has important 
 policy effects/results/suggestions for governments. If governments 
 decide to invest useful things/valuable supplies into helping poorness, 
 it is very important to know how social and public capital influence income generation. Incorporating social 
 capital and community level (numbers that change/things that change) representing 
 public capital into the analysis of valuable things and activities 
 has proved filled with problems since these valuable things are usually hard to measure in a way that truly represents 
 the clearly stated/particular attributes of these valuable things and reflects how 
 families secure benefits from them. We face/deal with 
 this issue by using factor analysis to identify specific 
 factors to represent social and public capital. 
 The rest of this paper is divided into four sections. Section 2 provides a idea-based background for 
 the relationship between valuable things, activities and income 
 and discusses the scientific plan for examining the 
 use of valuable things in income-creating activities. Section 
 3 uses the Mexico data to define the set of valuable things (away from cities) 
 Mexican household use for creating income. Participation in activities and returns to valuable things are examined 
 using the Taylor and Yunez-Naude (2000) scientific 
 approach. In Section 4, the issue of measuring and including social and public capital is talked to/looked at. Measures of these valuable things, calculated using factor analysis, 
 are then included in the activity equations. Finally, in 
 Section 5 ends/end results are discussed. 
 
 2. (away from cities) job plans: idea-based 
 (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) and scientific approach 
 The basis of a job plan is the valuable thing position of the household at a given point in time. Note 
 
 P Winters et al. I Farming-based Money flow 27 (2002) 139-156 
 
 that, as has become standard practice, household valuable things 
 are defined broadly to include natural, physical, human, (money-related), public, household and respect. 1 
 These valuable things are stocks, which may (lower in value) over 
 time or may be expanded through investment. Based 
 on access to a particular set of valuable things for a given period, the household must decide which activities it 
 will employ and the strength of involvement in that 
 activity. For purposes of this paper, activities are actions taken by the household to produce income. They 
 involve the use of a single valuable thing or a set of valuable things. 
 Farming-based production, for example, may use natural 
 capital in the form of land and water, workers, 
 physical capital such as tractors, (money-related) capital for 
 the (instance of buying something for money) of inputs and respect in the form 
 of labour help by community members. Or, non-farm wage employment may only use workers. The strength of an activity depends on 
 the degree to which valuable things are used. A plan of farming-based (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) is likely to involve a greater 
 use of workers and (money-related) capital (for the (instance of buying something for money) of inputs) than a plan that focuses on other 
 activities or in less intensive farming-based production. 
 The decision on the set of activities a household will 
 employ and the strength of those activities is conditioned on the big picture  in which the household operates. 
 The big picture  influences household decisions through 
 natural forces, markets, state activity and people-related institutions. 
 Mentally, the mapping of valuable things to income 
 through activities can be viewed as almost the same as  a production process, with valuable things going along with/matching up to factors 
 of production and income as the output of the process 
 (Barrett and Reardon, 2000). The return to valuable things depends on the limits/guidelines of the functions, which are 
 figured out by/decided by prices of inputs and outputs as well 
 as other (features/ qualities/ traits) of the big picture. The portion 
 of valuable things to each activity is expected to (make as big as possible) 
 household income subject to some restrictions. 
 Families will set apart valuable things in a manner that 
 equates the not important value product across activities 
 1 The types of capital that families access can be categorised 
 in a variety of manners. One common categorisation is to define 
 four types of capital: natural, human-made (physical), human and 
 social (Serageldin and Steer, !994). Our categorisation reflects a 
 want to provide greater detail in the types of capital used by 
 families although each of these categories can be absorbed in 
 one of the four categories commonly presented. 
 
