 or will set apart valuable things completely to one activity that has 
 a superior return. 
 One of the key features of this approach is that 
 families (at the same time) decide/figure out the portion of 
 valuable things to different activities. Failure to think about  the 
 (happening together) nature of the decision can lead to curious and often disagreeing results across different 
 studies. For example, Taylor and Yunez-Naude (2000) 
 note that research on the returns to schooling in (away from cities) 
 (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) range from high to negative. They argue 
 that the reason for this is that (people who work to find information) did not 
 take into account the (related to computers and science) changes and part/areaal (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) that describe farming-based change in developing countries. Families may 
 collect  the rewards from education through leaving alone (and forgetting) 
 or limiting one activity in favour of another. A low or 
 negative return to schooling in crop production, for example, may mean that the more educated have shifted 
 to other activities such as non-farm employment. (in almost the same way), this logic holds for all valuable things. If the government puts a paved road through to a community, this 
 may cause some families in that community to change  income-creating activities. (people who work to find information) focusing 
 on a single activity may find that investment in (set of machines) reduces income from that activity, which 
 may lead to mentally sick policy effects/results/suggestions. While this 
 may be the case, analysis of a single activity ignores 
 the benefits of (set of machines) in other activities. Only 
 through (thinking about/when one thinks about) all income-creating activities 
 (at the same time) can this problem be avoided. The issue we want to examine in this paper is the relative 
 importance of different valuable things in the activities chosen 
 by (away from cities) Mexican families, with particular focus on social and public valuable things. 
 The household's decision on the portion of valuable things 
 across activities is a (happening together) decision and one 
 that is changed by the fact that families do not 
 necessarily participate in all possible activities. Some 
 families will therefore have zero income from, for 
 example, self-employment. 2 Examining the portion 
 and returns to valuable things needs/demands a (happening together) equation 
 model in which the dependent income (numbers that change/things that change) are 
 changed by unobservable hidden/covered up (numbers that change/things that change) influencing 
