 the activity participation decision. Families get 
 income from an activity only if they participate in that 
 activity. Participation in an income-creating activity 
 happens if the household believes the expected returns 
 to that activity are greater than the other choice of not 
 participating. 
 The econometric approach follows Lee's (big statement based on very little information) of an guess way of thinking/basic truth/rule of Amemiya 
 (1977a,b) in a general (happening together) equation model. 
 
 Lee (1978) compared Amemiya's generalised twostage estimators with other two-stage estimators, 
 and showed that Amemiya's estimators are more 
 (producing a lot with very little waste) in all cases, including those proposed by 
 Heckman. This econometric (detailed description of exactly what is required) allows for 
 changed (things that change (like test scores) because of other things that you control (like study times)), where unobservable 
 hidden/covered up (numbers that change/things that change) influence the decision to participate in 
 an activity. (not very long ago), Taylor and Yunez-Naude (2000) 
 used Lee's (big statement based on very little information) in their study of returns 
 to schooling in both crop and non-crop activities in 
 (away from cities) Mexico and we follow their scientific approach. 
 In the first step, probits using the complete set of valuable thing 
 (numbers that change/things that change) as explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) are guessed. The 
 probit on each income-creating activity measures 
 the effects of valuable things on household participation in that 
 activity. The probits are also used to calculate inverse 
 Mill's ratios (IMR), which are included in the second 
 step to control for selectivity bias. The second step is 
 to guess the income equations, including an IMR 
 as a right-hand side (number or thing that changes) in each of the similar income equations. The income equations are 
 guessed both/together, to reflect the (happening together) nature 
 of the decision, for the full household sample using 
 three stage least squares which allows the including in something 
 of information contained in the cross-equation error 
 relationships. For the income equations, only valuable things 
 that are expected to affect the income level of that 
 activity are included as right-hand side (numbers that change/things that change). 
 The data used in this study comes from a nationally 
 representative sample of Mexican ejido, or land reform, families. 3 Data were collected at two points 
 in time during the Spring and early summer of 1994 
 and 1997, for 972 families. 4 The survey covered 
 a wide organized row of household valuable things as well as household 
 3 The ejido is the land reform (machine/method/way) used by the Mexican 
 government from the 1930s to 1992. Land and water supplies 
 were granted to a community or a group of producers, or ejido, 
 with each producer getting usufruct rights over a parcel and 
 access to common lands. A 1992 (agreeing with, or related to, the Constitution) reform ended the 
 distribution of land and established a process by which individual 
 titles may be given to ejidatarios, and by which ejidos may 
 decide to (turn over from the government to private companies) individual parcels. The ejido part/area covers 
 75% of all farming-based producers in Mexico (roughly 3 million 
 families), and over half of the country's watered and rainfed 
 land. 
 4 The (office of secretaries) of Land-related Reform and the World Bank carried out the surveys with help from the University of California, Berkeley. A described/explained description of the Mexico data and 
 its sampling properties can be found in Cord et a!. (1998). 
 
 P. Winters et al. I Farming-based Money flow 27 (2002) 139-156 
 
 (information about people/combinations of different kinds of people), income-creating activities and participation in organisations. Community-level data was 
 also collected on (features/ qualities/ traits) and organisation of 
 the ejido. Most of the data used in this analysis, including the income data, is from the 1997 survey except sometimes where 1994 data was used to avoid 
 endogeneity problems. 
 
