 3. Valuable things and income-creating activities 
 Household activities can be divided into six 
 categories: crop production, animals production, 
 self-employment, non-farming-based wage employment, farming-based wage employment and traveling. 
 Table I presents data on these activities. On average families earned 10,888 pesos in 1997. Not 
 all families participate in every activity. A majority of families participate in crop (93.7%) and 
 animals (75.3%) production but few participate in 
 self-employment (17.2%) and traveling (15.8%). 
 Farming-based activities (crops, animals and farming-based employment) make up 55% of total (away from cities) household income showing that nearly half of income is 
 created by non-farming-based activities. Crop income 
 represents about 30% of total income in 1997 and 
 is the most important source of income followed by 
 non-farming-based wage income (27 .1% ). However, only 
 42.3% of families participate in non-farming-based 
 wage employment and for those that do, it is the most 
 important income-creating activity (52.8% of total income). (in almost the same way), families that participate in 
 self-employment and traveling receive, on average, 
 one-third of their income from this activity. Some farming-based families have this way shifted away 
 from farming-based to non-farming-based activities. 
 Valuable thing ownership differs/changes significantly across the 
 ejido part/area. In Table 2, explanatory valuable things are grouped 
 into the following categories-natural (land), physical (animals, equipment), human (education, (male/female status), 
 labour, labour experience and (family and cultural characteristics)), (money-related) 
 (credit), and traveling (US and Mexico traveling networks) capital. (related to a large area) (numbers that change/things that change) are also included 
 to control for unseen factors. On average, families have much less watered land than either 
 rainfed or (area of grassy land) land. For the 25% of families 
 with watered land, average size is 5.2 ha. Although 
 overall families hold an average of 6.4 heads of 
 
