 that activity are not especially interesting. Rainfed 
 land and animals ownership positively influence participation in animals production while watered land 
 and tractor ownership are negatively connected with 
 animals participation. This is not surprising since 
 these latter valuable things are likely to have higher returns for 
 crop production. For a almost the same  reason, tractor owners 
 are less likely to participate in self-employment. Natural and physical capital reduces participation in both 
 forms of wage employment. The strong connection 
 between rainfed land and payment income may point to/show that participation in traveling needs/demands at least 
 a (almost nothing/very little) wealth level. Education, especially among 
 males, plays a strong role in non-farming-based wage employment. (almost nothing/very little) male education, or reading and writing ability, seems 
 to play a almost the same  role in animals production. Higher 
 levels of male education are negatively connected 
 with receipt of payments. Younger families (as 
 pointed to/showed by age of household head) are more likely 
 to participate in farming-based wage employment, and 
 older families in receiving payments. The presence of young males, controlling for education, leads 
 to increased participation in farming-based wage labour, 
 while the presence of older males leads to greater 
 participation in crop production. Previous experience in non-farming-based activities (self-employment 
 and non-farming-based wage earning), as expected, 
 leads to a greater chance of participation in each 
 (pertaining to each person or thing) activity. However, previous experience in 
 farming-based wage employment leads to greater participation in crop production, farming-based wage earning 
 and traveling. Somewhat surprisingly, access to formal credit in 1994 does not influence participation 
 in any activities in 1997. This could be because 
 credit is mostly tied to crop production. Native (to) 
 families are more likely to participate in on-farm 
 activities and less likely to move. Some 
 (related to a large area) (numbers that change/things that change) are related to particular activities suggesting there are certain (related to a large area) factors that 
 influence participation that are not controlled for in 
 the moving backward. Finally, traveling networks are most 
 important for receiving payment income. 
 Table 4 presents the results of the selectivity corrected system guesses of the income equations. 
 While the probits tested the chance of participation in activities, the income equations examine 
 the factors influencing the level of income from 
 each activity. Note that in all guesses, except for 
 
 self-employment, the IMR is significant at the 95% 
 level or above. This points to/shows that self-selection into 
 activities is an important factor in (thinking about/when one thinks about) the 
 income-created from a particular activity and failure to control for this would have led to (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) results. 
 Valuable things play a variety of roles in terms of the generation of income by activity. Land size, especially 
 watered land, is important for on-farm categories as 
 well as self-employment and payments. Rainfed 
 get is important for animals income, as it serves 
 as an input into animals production. Rainfed land is 
 also important for self-employment suggesting that 
 farmers with more land can earn more through 
 self-employment than others. Education provides the 
 most interesting story. Education is most important, 
 as expected, for non-farming-based wage labour, 
 though this differs/changes by (male/female status). All levels of male education lead to higher off-farm income, while only the 
 highest level of female education has a positive-and 
 significant-coefficient. On the other hand, the number of females (old/allowed to get old/got older) 15-34 years, holding education 
 constant, has a positive and significant effect, signalling that lower levels of female education are not 
 valued on the labour market. This is probably due 
 to the kind of entry level employment (away from cities) women 
 can choose from, such as domestic servant. Female 
 education is also important for self-employment income, and surprisingly, animals income. Both higher 
 levels of male and female education are connected 
 with higher farming-based income, suggesting that education only becomes important when it reaches a 
 certain technical level. 
 
 4. Adding social and public capital 
 The purpose of this section is to discuss a method 
 for including community (numbers that change/things that change), including social and public capital, in the analysis of 
 income-creating activities and to present the results 
 of the analysis. There has been some debate over 
 the exact definition and measure of respect 
 (Woolcock and Narayan, 2000). Respect can 
 be defined as a variety of different things/businesses with two 
 common elements: they all consist of some aspect of 
 social structure and they help actions of actors 
 within that structure (Coleman, 1988). For our purposes, respect makes up/is equal to the social relations, 
 both up-and-down and flat/left-and-right, that help help the 
 
 P. Winters et al./ Farming-based Money flow 27 (2002) 139-156 
 
 generation of income. Since our interest is in examining the community factors that help income generation, we focus on relations at that level. Families 
 may belong to a set of formal and informal organisations that may provide direct or indirect help 
 in money-based activities. For example, membership in a 
 women's group may provide information on market 
 opportunities for non-farm products. In addition to 
 membership in individual organisations, the ejidos in 
 which families live may be well or poorly organised which will also affect the families' ability to 
 create income. Finally, up-and-down ties to, for example, 
 organisations that provide technical help will 
 influence income-generation. Each of these is carefully thought about/believed as part of respect. Another valuable thing that 
 is hard to measure and plays an important role in 
 income generation is public capital, which involves 
 access to public products (that are bought and sold)  and services. These include a 
 range of services and (set of machines) from health care 
 and telephone access to electricity and paved roads. 
 Calculating the value of social and public capital 
 is complicated by the (many different kinds of people or things) and variety of indicators. Families belong to a range of organisations both formal and informal and ejidos may have 
 different types of organisational structure. (set of machines) and services differ in terms of their presence and 
 importance in a community. Table 5 lists a variety of 
 community (numbers that change/things that change) that may be used as public and 
 respect indicators. They range from measures of 
 ejido organisation and household participation in organisations to the distance to different public services, 
 
