 P. Winterset al./Agricultural Money flow 27 (2002) 139-156 
 
 the level of community (set of machines) and direct household access to publicly given infrastructure. 
 The challenge for analysing the benefits of social 
 and public capital in income-creating activities is 
 deciding/figuring out a method for using the information contained in this large set of (numbers that change/things that change). Two options have 
 generally been used. The first is to create a single 
 number-based index that is a weighted average of the 
 (connected/related) set of (numbers that change/things that change). A higher value for the index 
 hints, for example, greater respect. The index 
 is then used in later analysis such as moving backward 
 analysis of income generation. Narayan and Pritchett 
 (1999) use this approach to examine household income generation in (away from cities) Tanzania. The problem with 
 this approach is that it needs/demands strong and somewhat 
 random ideas (you think are true) about the weights for each 
 (number or thing that changes) in the grouping. What's more, this method 
 assumes that a single number-based index is (good) enough to 
 represent social or public capital. However, as with 
 other forms of capital, social and public capital are 
 not (a mixture of things that are all pretty much the same) things/businesses. The World Bank (2000), for 
 example, identifies three types of respect: (gluing or joining together/friendship forming), bridging and linking. A single index ignores this 
 possibility. Even if many indexes were to be created to measure the different types of social or public 
 capital, defining the different indexes would still be 
 random. 
 The second approach to including social and public 
 capital (numbers that change/things that change) in income analysis is to use all or 
 a subset of the (numbers that change/things that change) directly in income (moving backwards). For example, De Janvry and Sadoulet (2001) 
 in testing the (things that decide other things) of income in the ejido 
 part/area include social and institutional valuable things (native (to) household and access to technical help) 
 and locational (features/ qualities/ traits) (number of city-based  centres within 1 h, number of (away from cities) centres within an 
 hour and (related to a large area) dummies). One problem with this 
 approach is in deciding which (numbers that change/things that change) well enough 
 represent the presence of social and public capital. 
 Which (number or thing that changes) in Table 5, for example, represents 
 the level of (set of machines) in a community? The problem with including all or even a lot of 
 of (numbers that change/things that change) in moving backward analysis is that this (detailed description of exactly what is required) can lead to problems with degrees of freedom, 
 if the sample is not (good or well enough) large, and multicolinearity if, as is likely, the multiple social and public 
 capital (numbers that change/things that change) are highly related. In the presence 
 of multicolinearity, identification is not a problem 
 
 but with highly related (numbers that change/things that change) guesses are less 
 exact (Greene, 1997). 
 Given the faults/problems of these two methods in 
 this paper, a third method, factor analysis, is used to 
 incorporate social and public capital into the analysis 
 of income generation. The first (or most important) purpose of factor 
 analysis is to describe the relationships among many 
 (numbers that change/things that change) in terms of a few hidden (under), but unobservable, factors (Johnson and Wichern, 1988). Factor 
 analysis groups sets of (numbers that change/things that change) by their relationships 
 and each group of (numbers that change/things that change) represents a single hidden (under) construct or factor. 5 For example, Kline 
 and Wichelns (1996) use factor analysis to test 
 people who responded' perceptions of farmland preservation 
 programs. Based on reasons gave/given for preserving 
 farmland, they identify four factors that seem to explain preferences: (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) goals, beauty-related 
 goals, land-related goals and anti-growth goals. (in almost the same way), using the many measures of social 
 and public capital, the hidden (under) factors that represent the important (features/ qualities/ traits) of these valuable things can 
 be serious and stubborn. In one such study, Onyx and Bullen 
 (2000), using a set of 36 measures of respect 
 from five Australian communities, identify eight factors that represent respect including community 
 participation, (service business/government unit/power/functioning) and trust. While factor analysis 
 does help in identifying hidden (under) factors represented by a set of (numbers that change/things that change), the method is (not definite) 
 and needs/demands (understanding/ explanation) of the factors to give them 
 meaning. This (understanding/ explanation) depends on previous knowledge and gut feeling about hidden (under) relationships. 
 For this study, factor analysis was used to identify 
 factors that represent the important elements of social 
 and public capital. Social and public capital are not 
 necessarily (group of things that are all pretty much the same) and more than one factor 
 was expected to come out  for each set of (numbers that change/things that change). Social and public capital (numbers that change/things that change) were analysed using 
 the principal part-related factor method and rotated 
 using the varimax rotation method. 6 Usually, factors 
 5 Factor analysis is just like principal parts/pieces analysis 
 in that both are tries to come close to the covariance matrix. 
 However, factor analysis is more detailed and the first (or most important) question 
 it tries to ask is whether the data are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with some 
 hidden (under) structure (Johnson and Wichern, 1988). 
 6 As recommended as a first step by Johnson and Wichern 
 (1988). Added/more methods including the cycled-through principal factor 
 method and the maximum chance factor method were examined. Since these approaches tended to bring about almost the same  solutions the original principal parts/pieces factor method was used. 
 
 P. Winters et al.lAgricultural Money flow 27 (2002) 139-156 
 
 are kept/held in the analysis if their eigenvalues are 
 greater than one. To limit the number of factors kept/held the cut-off value was increased to 1.25, which 
 allows for a more plain/honest/easy (understanding/ explanation) of 
 factors. Even with this limitation, as will be seen 
 below, understanding/explaining some of the factors is hard. 
 At that cut-off, eight factors were kept/held which 
 represented 44% of the variance. 7 Results of the factor analysis are presented in Table 6. As is standard 
 practice, only factor loadings greater than 0.25 are 
 kept/held for (understanding/ explanation). 8 
 
 4.1. Factor 1: closeness 
 This factor points to/shows the closeness of the community to (set of machines), services and city-based  areas. This is 
 proven true by the high negative loadings on distance to 
 a health clinic ( -0.45), post office ( -0.84), telegraph 
 ( -0.80) and a fax ( -0.88), and the time ( -0.76) and 
 distance to an city-based  centre ( -0.84). Families with 
 a strong connection with this factor tend to be less remote than those negatively connected with this factor. 
 
 4.2. Factor 2: ejido population size 
 This factor is related to ejidos that have a big population, which exists along with access to 
 big community services and (set of machines). The 
 strong connections with DICONSA and LICONSA 
 stores, 9 as well as with the presence of a meeting 
 room, a secondary school and a high school show this. 
 The negative associations with distance to a health centre and to a post office also point to/show a large community 
 with access to those services. The negative association 
 with PROCEDE changes and the strong connection 
 with (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) worsening are indicators of the 
 co-operation problems connected with having a large 
 7 This goes along with the 49% of the variance explained by the 
 eight factors identified by Onyx and Bullen (2000). 
 8 While only one set of results is presented, some methods 
 of factor analysis were explored. Although the order of the factors 
 differed across method, the results were mostly the same across 
 methods. That is, the loadings and relevance of certain (numbers that change/things that change) 
 tended to be the same across methods suggesting these factors do 
 represent some hidden (under) structure in the data. 
 9 LICONSA is a federal program that provides give money tod milk 
 to very poor families, city-based  and (away from cities), with children under 
 12 years of age, and tortillas to very poor families, city-based 
 and (away from cities). 
 
 149 
 
 ejido-difficulty in organising the reform process and 
 difficulty in managing the useful thing/valuable supply base. 
 
 4.3. Factor 3: semi-city-based 
 This factor appears to represent ejidos that are 
 semi-city-based. The number of city-based  centres within an 
 hour has a large coefficient (0.62) as does the number 
 of (away from cities) centres within an hour (0.35). Because of this, it is not 
 surprising to see a strong connection with share of 
 roads that are paved, DICONSA store, meeting room, 
 secondary school and telephone access. An ejido near 
 an city-based  or (away from cities) centre is more likely to have greater 
 (set of machines) and services. There is also a positive 
 association with the PROCEDE reform. Since this 
 reform leads to the portion of individual property 
 rights, it is likely to be the case that the reform process will happen in areas where land can be more easily 
 sold or rented, as is generally the case in semi-city-based 
 areas. Finally, there is a positive relationship with 
 informal organisation participation. Again this could 
 be connected with a semi-city-based  setting where (groups of people/animals/things) tend to be denser and organising for cultural 
 and money-based reasons is easier. 
 
 4.4. Factor 4: co-operation 
 This factor clearly represents co-operation within 
 the ejido as proven true by the strong loading on families often participating in (groups of people/devices made up of smaller parts) (0.72), respecting community agreements (0.71) and belonging 
 to informal organisations (0.40). 
 
 4.5. Factor 5: lack of formal production 
 arrangements 
 This factor describes the lack of formal production 
 organisation in the ejido, as there is a strong negative association with an ejido belonging to an ARIC 10 
 ( -0.63). What's more, a big number of families connected with this factor do not participate in 
 'other' formal organisations ( -0.54), production contracts ( -0.48) and the government technology move (from one place to another) program ( -0.48). There is a somewhat weird 
 10 ARIC, the Spanish (word made up from the first letters of words) for (away from cities) Associations of Total Interests, are organisations of ejidos that (help increase/show in a good way) common 
 goals. 
 
